2 DETAILS VAN DE AANVRAAG


2.1 Aanvraag

Het betreft een aanvraag tot uitbreiding van het gebruiksgebied van het middel Fubol Gold (12537 N), een middel op basis van de werkzame stoffen  mancozeb en metalaxyl-m. Het middel is bij besluit van 26 maart 2004 reeds toegelaten als schimmelbestrijdingsmiddel in de teelt van consumptie- en zetmeelaardappelen, zaaiuien, 2e jaars plantuien, plantsjalotten, zaaisjalotten, zilveruien en picklers, boomkwekerijgewassen en in de teelt van Helichrysum in de vollegrond. Het middel is bij dit besluit toegelaten tot 1 december 2008. Met onderliggende aanvraag wordt toelating als schimmelbestrijdingsmiddel voor sla gevraagd.


2.2 Informatie met betrekking tot de werkzame stoffen

Mancozeb

Mancozeb is een oude stof voor de EU. De stof wordt geplaatst op Bijlage I van richtlijn 91/414/EEG per 1 juli 2006. Er is een monografie beschikbaar


Metalaxyl-M

Metalaxyl-M is een nieuwe stof voor de EU. De stof is geplaatst op Bijlage I van richtlijn 91/414/EEG op 1 oktober 2002.


2.3 Karakterisering van het middel

Fubol Gold is een combinatiemiddel van 4 % metalaxyl-m en 64% mancozeb.

Metalaxyl-M is een systemisch werkend fungicide met een preventieve en curatieve werking. De stof wordt opgenomen door de bladeren, stengels en wortels. Metalaxyl-M is de actieve isomeer van de stof metalaxyl. Door gebruik van uitsluitend de actieve isomeer is de totale hoeveelheid werkzame stof die per ha. moet worden toegepast met de helft verlaagd.

Metalaxyl-m behoort tot de fungicide groep phenylamiden. Deze groep wordt onderverdeeld in 3 subgroepen nl. acylalaninen, butyrolacetonen en oxazole ketonen. Metalaxyl-m behoort tot de subgroep acylalazinen, hiertoe behoort ook de stof furalaxyl. Deze stoffen remmen de eiwit synthese van de schimmels. Deze stoffen zijn werkzaam tegen Oรถmyceten zowel de grondgebonden soorten als die welke zich door de lucht verspreiden.

Mancozeb behoort tot de groep van dithiocarbamaten en heeft een multi-site werking. De kans op resistentie bij dergelijke stoffen is zeer klein. Mancozeb blokkeert de stofwisseling van schimmels en werkt preventief.


2.4 Voorgeschiedenis

De aanvraag is ontvangen op 14 oktober 2005 ontvangen. Op 19 oktober 2005 zijn de verschuldigde aanvraagkosten ontvangen. Op 19 januari 2006 is de aanvraag in behandeling genomen. Op 25 januari 2006 zijn de verschuldigde beoordelingskosten ontvangen. De 34 โweken termijn eindigt op 20 september 2006.


3 RISICOBEOORDELINGEN 


3.1 Fysische en chemische eigenschappen

De geleverde gegevens geven in voldoende mate de mogelijkheid om op basis daarvan de identiteit van het middel vast te stellen, te specificeren en te karakteriseren. Er is vastgesteld dat de standaardgegevens voor milieu, toxicologische aspecten en risicoโs met betrekking tot de fysisch-chemische eigenschappen beschikbaar zijn (artikel 3, lid 1, sub d Bmw 1962).

De beoordeling van de evaluatie van het middel en de stof staat beschreven in Bijlage II, Hoofdstuk 2. Physical and chemical properties behorende bij dit besluit.


3.2 Analysemethoden

De geleverde analysemethoden voldoen aan de vereisten. De residuanalysemethoden zijn specifiek en gevoelig genoeg om te kunnen worden gebruikt voor het controleren van de betreffende plantaardige en dierlijke producten op het maximaal toegestane gehalte, en het monitoren van de verspreiding van de residuen in het milieu (artikel 3, lid 1, sub b en c Bmw 1962).

De beoordeling van de evaluatie van de analysemethoden staat beschreven in Bijlage II, Hoofdstuk 3. Methods of analysis behorende bij dit besluit.


3.3 Humane Toxicologie

Er is vastgesteld dat het middel en zijn omzettingsproducten, wanneer het overeenkomstig het bepaalde bij of krachtens de Bestrijdingsmiddelenwet 1962 wordt gebruikt:

  • de gezondheid niet schaadt of de veiligheid niet in gevaar brengt van degene die het middel toepast, en

  • de gezondheid niet schaadt of de veiligheid niet in gevaar brengt van diegenen, die na toepassing van het middel door verrichten van werkzaamheden daarmee of met de residuen daarvan in aanraking komen (artikel 3, lid 1, sub a, onderdelen 5 en 6 Bmw 1962).

Het profiel humane toxicologie inclusief de beoordeling van het risico voor de toepasser staat beschreven in Bijlage II, Hoofdstuk 4. Mammalian toxicology behorende bij dit besluit.


3.4 Residuen en risico voor de volksgezondheid

Er is vastgesteld dat het middel en zijn omzettingsproducten, wanneer het overeenkomstig het bepaalde bij of krachtens de Bestrijdingsmiddelenwet 1962 wordt gebruikt geen schadelijke uitwerking heeft op de gezondheid van de mens (artikel 3, lid 1, sub a, onderdeel 3 Bmw 1962).

De vastgestelde maximum residuniveaus en de beoordeling van het risico voor de volksgezondheid staan beschreven in Bijlage II, Hoofdstuk 5. Residues behorende bij dit besluit.


3.5 Gedrag in bodem, water en lucht

Er is vastgesteld dat het middel en zijn omzettingsproducten, wanneer het overeenkomstig het bepaalde bij of krachtens de Bestrijdingsmiddelenwet 1962 wordt gebruikt

  • geen schadelijke uitwerking heeft op het grondwater en)

  • geen voor het milieu onaanvaardbaar effect heeft, waarbij in het bijzonder rekening wordt gehouden met:

  • de plaats waar het bestrijdingsmiddel in het milieu terecht komt en wordt verspreid, met name voor wat betreft besmetting van het water, met inbegrip van drink- en grondwater en belasting van de bodem;

  • de gevolgen voor niet doel-soorten

(artikel 3, lid 1, sub a, onderdelen 9 en 10 Bmw 1962).

Het profiel milieu inclusief de beoordeling van het risico voor het milieu staat beschreven in Bijlage II, Hoofdstuk 6. Environmental fate and behaviour behorende bij dit besluit.


3.6 Ecotoxicologie

Er is vastgesteld dat het middel en zijn omzettingsproducten, wanneer het overeenkomstig het bepaalde bij of krachtens de Bestrijdingsmiddelenwet 1962 wordt gebruikt

  • geen voor het milieu onaanvaardbaar effect heeft, waarbij in het bijzonder rekening wordt gehouden met:

  • de plaats waar het bestrijdingsmiddel in het milieu terecht komt en wordt verspreid, met name voor wat betreft besmetting van het water, met inbegrip van drink- en grondwater en belasting van de bodem;

  • de gevolgen voor niet doel-soorten (artikel 3, lid 1, sub a, onderdeel 10 Bmw 1962).

Het profiel ecotoxicologie inclusief de beoordeling van het risico voor niet-doelwit soorten staat beschreven in Bijlage II, Hoofdstuk 7. Ecotoxicology behorende bij dit besluit.


3.7 Werkzaamheid

Er is vastgesteld dat het middel en zijn omzettingsproducten, wanneer het overeenkomstig het bepaalde bij of krachtens de Bestrijdingsmiddelenwet 1962 wordt gebruikt:

  • voldoende werkzaam is en

  • geen onaanvaardbare uitwerking heeft op planten of plantaardige producten (artikel 3, lid 1, sub a, onderdelen 1 en 2 Bmw 1962).

De beoordeling van het aspect werkzaamheid staat beschreven in Bijlage II, Hoofddstuk 8. Efficacy behorende bij dit besluit.


3.8 Eindconclusie

Bij gebruik volgens het gewijzigde Wettelijk Gebruiksvoorschrift/Gebruiksaanwijzing is de uitbreiding voor de gevraagde doeleinden van het middel Fubol Gold op basis van de werkzame stoffen  mancozeb en metalaxyl-m voldoende werkzaam en heeft het geen schadelijke uitwerking op de gezondheid van de mens en het milieu (artikel 3 van de Bestrijdingsmiddelenwet 1962).



Degene wiens belang rechtstreeks bij dit besluit is betrokken kan gelet op artikel 8 van de Bestrijdingsmiddelenwet 1962 en artikel 7:1, eerste lid, van de Algemene wet bestuursrecht, binnen zes weken na de dag waarop dit besluit bekend is gemaakt een bezwaarschrift indienen bij: het College voor de Toelating van Bestrijdingsmiddelen (Ctb), Postbus 217, 6700 AE WAGENINGEN. A.

Wettelijk gebruiksvoorschrift



Toegestaan is uitsluitend het gebruik als schimmelbestrijdingsmiddel

  1. in de teelt van consumptie- en zetmeelaardappelen;

  2. in de teelt van zaaiuien, 2e jaars plantuien, plantsjalotten, zaaisjalotten, zilveruien en picklers;

  3. in de onbedekte teelt van sla, met uitzondering van veldsla;

  4. in de teelt van boomkwekerijgewassen en

  5. in de onbedekte teelt van Helichrysum in de vollegrond.


Toepassing is niet toegestaan van 1 september tot 1 maart.

 

Dit middel is gevaarlijk voor niet-doelwit arthropoden. Vermijd onnodige blootstelling.


Het is verboden dit middel met een luchtvaartuig toe te passen.


Om resistentieopbouw te voorkomen dit product of andere producten die metalaxyl-m of verwante stoffen bevatten, niet vaker gebruiken dan drie maal per seizoen. 


Veiligheidstermijn

De termijn tussen de laatste toepassing en de oogst mag niet korter zijn dan:

7 dagen voor consumptie- en zetmeelaardappelen.

14 dagen voor zaaiuien, 2e jaars plantuien, plantsjalotten, zaaisjalotten, zilveruien en picklers en sla.


B.

Gebruiksaanwijzing



Toepassingen


Consumptie- en fabrieksaardappelen: ter bestrijding van aardappelziekte (Phytophthora infestans)

Het middel vroeg in het seizoen toepassen als het gewas nog in volle ontwikkeling is (voor de bloei). Het verdient daarbij aanbeveling de eerste bespuiting uit te voeren met een ander geschikt middel. Toepassen met een interval van 7 tot 10 dagen afhankelijk van de infectiedruk. Maximaal drie opeenvolgende bespuitingen uitvoeren en binnen 7 dagen na de laatste bespuiting met Fubol Gold de bestrijding voortzetten met een ander daarvoor toegelaten middel. Niet toepassen op gewassen met stagnerende groei en op gewassen waar een aantasting zichtbaar is (i.v.m. resistentie). Om verspreiding van resistente schimmelstammen via het pootgoed te vermijden mag het middel niet in de teelt van pootaardappelen worden toegepast.

Dosering: 2,5 kg/ha.





Zaaiuien, 2e jaars plantuien, plantsjalotten, zaaisjalotten, zilveruien en picklers, ter bestrijding van valse meeldauw (Peronospora destructor)

Een behandeling uitvoeren zodra infectie is opgetreden en om de circa 7 dagen herhalen, naar gelang de weersomstandigheden en de toestand van het gewas.

Dosering: 2 kg per ha


Sla in onbedekte teelt met uitzondering van veldsla, ter bestrijding van valse meeldauw (Bremia lactucae)

Een behandeling uitvoeren zodra er, gelet op weersomstandigheden of op basis van een waarschuwingssysteem, kans op aantasting is. Volgende behandeling(en) uitvoeren in een interval van 7-14 dagen afhankelijk van de weersomstandigheden en ziektedruk. Zonodig kan een eerste behandeling op het plantbed worden uitgevoerd. Maximaal drie maal per teelt toepassen.

Dosering: 2,5 kg per ha


Roos en Vitis: tegen valse meeldauw (Pseudopernospora sparsa en Peronospora viticola)

Een bespuiting uitvoeren zodra aantasting wordt waargenomen. De bespuiting zonodig herhalen.

Dosering: 0,3% (300 gram per 100 liter water).


Helichrysum in de vollegrond: tegen valse meeldauw (Bremia lactucae)

Zodra aantasting wordt waargenomen of als het gewas nagenoeg gesloten is en aantasting wordt verwacht twee bespuitingen uitvoeren met een interval van zeven tot tien dagen. Daarna overgaan op een preventief spuitschema met andere daarvoor toegelaten middelen.

Dosering: 0,3% (300 gram per 100 liter water).


N.B.: Gevoelige gewassen

Indien nog geen ervaring is opgedaan met het middel, dient een proefbespuiting

uitgevoerd te worden teneinde de verdraagzaamheid van het gewas te testen.

3.1. Analytical methods in technical material and plant protection product

Technical as (principle of method)

Mancozeb

Sample digestion in sulfuric acid solution to produce carbon disulfide which is aspirated through a lead acetate solution absorber to remove hydrogen sulfide; carbon disulfide is absorbed in methanolic potassium hydroxide to form potassium xanthate which is neutralized and titrated with iodine solution to the starch end point. Sulfide is determined by removing the lead acetate trap from the train, reanalyzing the sample and calculating sulfide from the difference in the two results. Presented methods are more or less following CIPAC 61/1/M/1.2

Study conducted demonstrates the precision of the method: RSD = 0.34-0.63% (for sample containing mean wt% concentration of 36.3% to 99.4%carbamate complex)

Titration methods are absolute method, thus linearity data not apply to this type of method

The minor changes to CIPAC method are acceptable.



Metalaxyl-m

GC with FID (sum of 2 enantiomers)

HPLC (chiral) with UV detection (separate enantiomers)

Impurities in technical as (principle of method)

Mancozeb

Extraction with zinc chloride solution; reversed phase HPLC with UV detection at 233 nm and methanol/acetonitrile/water mobile phase and multilevel linear external standard calibration with a working standard.


ETU is extracted from the sample with methanol. After centrifugation and dilution the amount of ETU is determined by HPLC using UV-detection at 230 nm with N,N,N'-trimethylthiourea as internal standard


Extraction: with 2.03 % ammonium hydroxide in acetone. Clean-up: TLC on a 20 cm x 20 cm glass sheet covered with a 25 ยตm layer of silica, developed in an acetone/ammonium hydroxide 98 :2 solution. Determination: measurement of UV absorption at
231 nm. The percent ETU is calculated from calibration data. LOD=0.005%


For determination of ETU content, an in-house method involves Zinc chloride extraction of samples instead of methanol extraction procedure CIPAC MT 162 - HPLC/UV-detection (233 nm) - LOD= 0.00009%

Method validated

The test system is a sealed, 160 ml reaction flask, charged with 4.0 grams of ground test sample, 10% EDTA solution (to make 10 ml total volume), and 15 ml HCl/stannous chloride (8N/3%) reagent. An aliquot of the head space is injected into a gas chromatograph chromatograph with a flame photometric detector in the sulfur mode, where the sample responses are compared to a similarly prepared and injected EBDC standard.

LOD: 0.02-0.05 mg/kg.


Wheat (grains and straw), potatoes (tubers and leaves), spinach, celery, celeriac, barley, lettuce and apples are analysed by the method. 4.1 Toxicity of the formulated product (IIIA 7.1)

The formulation Fubol Gold does not need to be classified on the basis of its acute oral (LD50 rat >2000 mg/kg bw), dermal (LD50 rat >2000 mg/kg bw), and inhalation toxicology (LC50 rat >5.16 mg/L).

The formulation Fubol Gold does not need to be classified for dermal irritation or eye irritation.

Fubol Gold was negative in a Buehler test for skin sensitisation. No scientific motivation was given for not performing a more sensitive M&K or LLNA test. Since Fubol Gold contains mancozeb in a content exceeding 1%, and mancozeb is classified for skin sensitization. the formulation Fubol Gold needs to be classified with R43: May cause sensitisation by skin contact.


4.1.1 Data requirements formulated product

No additional data requirements are identified.


4.2 Dermal absorption (IIIA 7.3)


Mancozeb


The values in the list of end points are representative for the formulation Fubol Gold. However, the values are the sum of the radioactivity found directly after 8 hours exposure in urine, faeces, carcass and stripped skin. After the end of the 8 hours exposure total radioactivity in these compartments was ca. 0.6% indicating transport from the stratum corneum to the body after the end of the exposure. Therefore systemic exposure is calculated with 0.6% dermal absorption.


Metalaxyl-M


The values in the list of end points were obtained with an EC formulation. They are regarded as worst case for a granular formulation like Fubol Gold.

4.7 Combination toxicology

The formulation Fubol Gold is a mixture of two active substances, mancozeb and metalaxyl-M. The combined toxicological effect of these two active substances has not been investigated with regard to repeated dose toxicity. The combined exposure to these active substances may lead to a different toxicological profile than the profile that is based on the individual substances


Since the estimated exposure to these substances is only a small fraction of the AOEL, no additional risks are expected form the combined exposure.

5.1 Summary of residue data


5.1.1 Metabolism in plants

In the DAR on metalaxyl-M, metabolism was studied in grapevine (fruit), lettuce and tobacco (leafy crops) and potato (root and tuber vegetables).

In the DAR on mancozeb, metabolism was studied in pulses and oilseed (soybeans), fruiting vegetables (tomato), root vegetables (potatoes, sugar beet), and cereals (wheat). Leafy crops were not envestigated. However, as the metabolism in mancozeb is quite similar in the four crop categories investigated, it can be concluded that metabolism of mancozeb in lettuce will be similar to the metabolism in the other crop categories.


5.1.2 Metabolism in livestock

See the lists of end points for metalaxyl-M and mancozeb


5.1.3 Residue definition (plant and animal)

See the lists of end points for metalaxyl-M and mancozeb. The residue definition is also applicable to lettuce as the use in lettuce is covered by the metabolism studies.


5.1.4 Stability of residues

See the lists of end points for metalaxyl-M and mancozeb


5.1.5. Residue data

Mancozeb

No supervised residue trials in lettuce are available in the Draft assessment report (DAR) on mancozeb.

Twentyseven supervised residue trials in lettuce conducted in Northern-Europe are available.

The trials were performed according to GLP. Six trials were performed according to the intended use (3 applications of 1185-1600 g ai/ha; interval 6-9 days, PHI = 14 days) The residue levels found in these trials amount to 0.4 (3x), 0.5, 0.59 and 1.2 mg/kg. In two trials the interval was to long (8-12 days), the other characteristics of the trials were according to the GAP (residue levels found: 2.5, 0.24 mg/kg). In the other trials the dose applied was to low and/or only 2 applications were performed.

Lettuce is a major crop, therefore, a minimum of 8 residue trials are required. A sufficient number of residue trials is available.

These residue levels are in compliance with the harmonised EU-MRL established in (Directive 93/58/EEC).

Metalaxyl-M

In the Draft assessment report (DAR) for metalaxyl-M, 68 supervised residue trials in lettuce are available. Thirty trials were conducted in Northern Europe (11 indoor, 21 field), 23 field trials were conducted in Southern Europe, 8 field trials were conducted in the USA and five trials were conducted in Canada. Only the field trials in Northern Europe and Canada will be considered.

It is unknown whether the trials were performed according to GLP. Only four trials were performed according to the intended use. In two trials in Canada, metalaxyl-M was applied as a soil treatment. In the other nineteen trials, metalaxyl-M was applied in a overdose
(2 to 4 applications of 240-400 g as/ha).

The analysed residue values for the trials conducted according to the cGAP amount to 0.02 (2x) and 0.03 (2x) mg/kg.

The analysed residue values for the trials conducted with an overdose amount to <0.02 (4x), 0.02, <0.04, 0.04 (2x), <0.05 (4x), 0.06, 0.08, 0.09 (2x), 0.10, 0.13, 0.21, 0.46 mg/kg.

Lettuce is a major crop, therefore, a minimum of 8 residue trials are required. A sufficient number of residue trials is available.

These residue levels are in compliance with the harmonised EU-MRL of 2 mg/kg established in Directive 2003/60/EC

5.1.9 Calculation of the ADI and the ARfD

Mancozeb

In the final review report the ADI for mancozeb is set at 0,05 mg/kg bw/day, based on a 2-year carcinogenicity study in the rat with a NOAEL of 4,8 mg/kg bw/day, with the application of a safety factor for inter- and intraspecies differences of 100. For ETU an ADI of 0,002 mg/kg bw/day is set, based on 2-year study in the rat with a NOAEL of 0,37 mg/kg bw/day. Because of the teratogene effects of ETU a safety factor of 200 is applied.


For mancozeb the ARfD is based on the NOEL of 60 mg/kg bw/d in the rat teratogenicity study. Application of a safety factor for inter- and intraspecies differences of 100 results in an ARfD of 0.6 mg/kg bw/day (see the List of Endpoints for mammalian toxicology).

For ETU the ARfD is based on the NOAEL of 5 mg/kg bw/d in the rat teratogenicity study. Application of a safety factor for inter- and intraspecies differences of 100 results in an ARfD of 0.05 mg/kg bw/day (see the List of Endpoints for mammalian toxicology).


Metalaxyl-M

The ADI is based on the NOAEL of 8 mg/kg bw/d in the 90-day, 6-month, 1-year and 2-year study in the dog. Application of a safety factor for inter- and intraspecies differences of 100 results in an ADI of 0.08 mg/kg bw/day (see the List of Endpoints for mammalian toxicology).


No ARfD is derived, since metalaxyl-M has no acute toxic properties.


5.2 Maximum Residue Levels

Mancozeb

Harmonised EU-MRLs have been established for mancozeb in Directives 93/58/EC, for lettuce an MRL of 5 mg/kg has been established.

The LOD is 0,05 mg/kg en the residue is defined as the sum of CS2 (for the dithiocarbamates: maneb, mancozeb, metiram, propineb and zineb). As mancozeb is included in Annex I of directive 91/414/EC, the harmonized MRLs will be re-evaluated in the (near) future.

The residue levels found in residue trials available for mancozeb in lettuce comply with the
EU-MRL.


Metalaxyl-M

Provisional EU-MRLs have been established in Directive 2005/76/EC.

The MRLs for lettuce is based on trials in the DAR. As residue levels found in the four trials are lower than the (p)EU-MRL of 2 mg/kg, it is not expected that residues of metalaxyl-M will exceed this MRL when used according to the intended use for Fubol Gold.


MRLs in the Dutch residue directive โRegeling Residuenโ are established as their dithiocarbamates equivalent. Not all of these MRLs not comply with the EU Directive, these MRLs are recorded in italics between hyphens. See also table R.1. in appendix a.


The product complies with the MRL Directives. Notification of the MRLs is not necessary.


5.3 Consumer risk assessment

Metalaxyl-M

Risk assessment for chronic exposure through diet

Based on the proposed residue tolerances, a calculation of the National Theoretical Maximum Daily Intake (NTMDI) was carried out using the National Dutch diet and the (provisional) EU-MRLs. Calculation of the NTMDI shows that 6.0% and 16.1% of the ADI is used for the general population and for children, respectively.


Risk assessment for acute exposure through diet

A calculation of the National Estimated Short Term Intake was not performed, as an ARfD was not necessary.


Mancozeb

Risk assessment for chronic exposure through diet

A lengthy deliberation concerning the intake calculation was already given in C-110.3.8 of May 21st, 2001. The following text is a translation of the deliberation in C-110.3.8 of May 21st, 2001. The text has been altered in 146.3.5 of May 12th, 2004.


The EBDCโs have a similar toxicological mechanism. Furthermore, technically, no difference can be made between the different substances, because of the general residue definition. Therefore, a combined risk assessment of the exposure for the consumer must be conducted.

When assessing the exposure of the consumer to EBDCโs through the diet, the harmonised EU-MRLs should be used as a basis.

The consumer can be exposed to residues on Dutch products, but also to residues on imported products, for which EU-MRLโs have been established.

In the CCPR of 1998 it was decided that the risk assessment should be corrected for the different ADIโs of the different dithiocarbamates. It was also decided that the dithiocarbamate pesticides needed to be devided in two groups, based on two different toxicological profiles. Formulations that are toxic for the thyroid, based on the active substances mancozeb, maneb, metiram, propineb and zineb, and formulations that are not toxic for the thyroid (based on ferbam, thiram and ziram)

The risk assessment that was conducted for this evaluation follows the approach of the JMPR (1996) and which was reported to the CCPR in document CX/PR 97/8. The approach uses a toxic equivalent correction factor, which was based on the lowest ADI in the group of EBDCโs. Another correction factor should be used to convert the MRL, expressed as CS2, to the amount of parent substance (molecular weight/ CS2 weight), in which the ADI is expressed.

A combined correction factor results by multiplying the toxic equivalent correction factor with the correction factor for the conversion of the parent substance.

The latter factor is used to correct the established MRL or STMR for a product and which has the highest combined correction factor of the dithicarbamate concerned. The lowest ADI value is used for the intake calculation.

Thus a carefully considered intake calculation can be conducted of the EBDCโs with different ADIโs.

The risk assessment was based on the dithiocarbamates maneb, mancozeb, metiram and propineb. In the Netherlands there are no authorisation for formulations with the active substance propineb, but propineb is authorized in other member states. Zineb is no longer authorized in the EU and is not taken into account in the calculation.

In the table below, the correction factors for the different dithiocarbamates are presented.

The toxic equivalent correction factor is based on propineb, as this substance has the lowest ADI of al four dithicoarbamates in question.

In the intake calculation in C-110.3.8 all uncertainties which arise from overestimations caused by processing factors and the mean residue levels are reported in detail. The following risk assessment was conducted, all information mentioned above was taken into account.


A calculation of the National Theoretical Maximum Daily Intake (NTMDI) was carried out using the National Dutch diet and the EU-MRLs for dithiocarbamates. Calculation of the NTMDI shows that 815% and 2071% of the ADI is used for the general population and for children ages 1-6, respectively.


The TMDI-calculation reveals an exceeding, however this is an overestimation of the intake in reality. Therefore a refinement of the risk assessment for mancozeb was conducted with the help of STMRs and processing factors.

It was assumed that the STMR is 1/3 of the MRL value. Processing data are available for oranges, wine grapes and tomatoes. With the help of these processing data a NEDI-calculation was performed, which shows that 125% and 224% of the ADI is used for the general population and for children ages 1-6, respectively.


Besides processing data for oranges, wine grapes and tomatoes, processing data are also available for banana. Processing factors are available for four commodities, and unavailable for 42 other commodities. De reduction factors amount to a factor 5 to 60. It was assumed that a reduction factor of 5 to 60 also applies for the other 42 commodities.

Presuming a reduction factor of only 5, the estimated intake of mancozeb for the general population as well as children ages 1-6 are well below the ADI.


As the ADI for dithiocarbamates is not exceeded when mancozeb is used on all the crops for which EU-MRLs have been established, no risk for the consumer due to the exposure to is currently expected.

Risk assessment for acute exposure through diet

A calculation of the National Estimated Short Term Intake (NESTI) was carried out using the National Dutch diet (โlarge portion sizesโ; 97.5 percentile from dietary data), the UK โunit weightsโ and previously mentioned harmonised EU-MRLs for lettuce. The NESTI uses 5.1 % and 10.4 % of the ARfD for the general population and for children, respectively.


ETU

Risk assessment for chronic exposure through diet

ETU is a relevant metabolite from a toxicological point of view. In the monographs an ADI of 0.002 mg/kg bw/day has been proposed. ETU is mostly a reaction product of the parent compound after heating. In the Dutch Residue Directive (Regeling residuen) an MRL of
0.1 mg/kg is established for heated food and beverages.


In the EU and in the CODEX no MRLโs for ETU have been established. In the past the CODEX proposed MRLโs for ETU, however, these were revoked in 1995. This because of the fact that residues of ETU do not give a correct indication on the use of EBDCโs and because of the fact that there is no connection between ETU residues in processed and non-processed products.

In the Dutch Residue Directive โRegeling Residuenโ an MRL of 0.1 mg/kg for all heated food and beverages is established.


As ETU is mainly present in heated products as a degradation product of dithiocarbamates, the amount of ETU will always be lower than the amount of CS2.

From processing data it was concluded that the ETU concentration is a factor 4 to 10 lower than the amount CS2. The ADI of ETU (0,002 mg/kg bw) is (only) a factor 2,5 lower than the ADI of propineb. Thus it was concluded that since the chronic intake of CS2 is acceptable, the chronic intake of ETU is also acceptable.


Risk assessment for acute exposure through diet

The NESTI calculation for ETU on lettuce shows that the acute intake for the general population is 1.2 % and 2.5 % for children ages 1-6.

In de calculation the Dutch MRL of 0.1 was used as HR. As ETU is formed after heating and lettuce is not normally heated as a processing step, no significant ETU residues are expected in lettuce.

Therefore it can be concluded that the NESTI calculation is an extreme worst-case calculation. In reality, an acute risk for the consumer is not expected because of the consumption of lettuce treated with mancozeb.


Conclusion


Based on the assessment for residues, no risk for the consumer due to the exposure to metalaxyl-M and mancozeb is currently expected.

Non-relevant metabolites (in Dutch, taken from assessment Fubol Gold WG, decision of 2005)


Metalaxyl-M

De aanvrager heeft een beroep gedaan op het niet-relevant zijn van CGA 62826 (mA) en CGA 108906 (mB). Hiervoor zijn nadere gegevens geleverd. In het volgende wordt getoetst of mA en mB aan de criteria voldoen.

Werkzaamheid: Metaboliet mA en mB hebben geen fungicide werking, er wordt voldaan aan het criterium voor niet-relevantie.

Ecotoxicologie: De gegevens voor mA zijn ontleend aan het rapport van ECCO-meeting 100, de onderliggende studies zijn niet beoordeeld.

De 72-uurs NOEC van mA voor Scenedesmus subspicatus is 100 mg/L, de 72-uurs NOEC van mB voor S. subspicatus is 21 mg/L (N.B.: in de eindpuntenlijst staat 74 mg/L). De 48-uurs EC50 van mA voor Daphnia magna is 852 mg/L, de 48-uurs EC50 van mB voor D. magna is >
100 mg/L. De 96-uurs LC50โs van mA en mB voor Oncorhynchus mykiss zijn >100 mg/L. Hiermee voldoen mA en mB aan de criteria voor niet-relevantie wat betreft het aquatische ecosysteem.

De 14-daagse LC50 van mA en mB voor Eisenia andrei is >1000 mg/kg en mA en mB hebben bij relevante concentraties geen effect op bodemmicro-organismen. Hiermee voldoen mA en mB aan de criteria voor niet-relevantie voor wat betreft het terrestrische ecosysteem.

Humane toxicologie: Metaboliet mA en mB zijn wat betreft humane toxicologie niet-relevant bevonden, zie beoordeling toxicologie.


Op basis van het bovenstaande kan geconcludeerd worden dat de metabolieten mA en mB gering schadelijk zijn en zodoende niet getoetst hoeven te worden aan de milieunormen zoals opgenomen in de UB.


Mancozeb

In Addendum 1 van de monograph van mancozeb zijn studies opgenomen waaruit blijkt dat EU weinig giftig is voor alg, kreeftachtige en vis (L(E)C50 > 100 mg/L) en voor regenwormen

(LC50 > 1000 mg/kg). In een studie met bodemmicro-organismen zijn geen effecten van EU waargenomen. De metaboliet vertoont geen werkzaamheid en is daarnaast humaan-toxicologisch niet relevant. EU kan derhalve ten aanzien van de milieueffecten als een niet relevante metaboliet worden aangemerkt en behoeft geen toetsing aan de norm voor uitspoeling volgens het Besluit milieutoelatingseisen bestrijdingsmiddelen (Bmb).

6.1.1 Persistence in soil (in Dutch, taken from assessment Fubol Gold WG, decision of

Beoordeling metalaxyl-M

De mediane DT50 van metalaxyl-M onder laboratoriumomstandigheden bij 20-25ยฐC is

20 dagen (range 7-58,4 dagen). De mineralisatie na 100 dagen is ca. 1-38%, de hoeveelheid grondgebonden residu is 2,3-73% na 100 dagen. Onder veldomstandigheden is de mediane DT50 38,7 dagen (range 19,5-113 dagen). Metalaxyl-M heeft dus zowel onder lab- als onder veldomstandigheden een gemiddelde DT50-waarde van < 90 dagen en voldoet hiermee aan de norm voor persistentie in de bodem van de Uniforme Beginselen (UB).


Alleen metaboliet CGA 62826 (mA) wordt >10% gevormd in de bodem (maximaal vormingspercentage 40,36 %). Deze heeft een DT50lab van 14,9 dagen en een DT50veld van 31,2 dagen. Aangezien deze metaboliet niet-relevant is verklaard (zie bovenstaand) kan deze worden uitgesloten van toetsing aan de norm voor persistentie volgens de Uniforme Beginselen (UB).

 

Beoordeling mancozeb

Voor de werkzame stof mancozeb is de DT50lab-waarde geschat op 1 tot 3 uur. Tevens kan met voldoende zekerheid worden uitgesloten dat na 100 dagen er meer dan 70% grondgebonden residu van de begindosis in combinatie met minder dan 5% CO2 van de begindosis zal zijn gevormd. Daarmee wordt voor wat betreft mancozeb voldaan aan de norm voor persistentie zoals opgenomen in Besluit milieutoelatingseisen bestrijdingsmiddelen (Bmb).


De metabolieten EBIS, ETU en EU worden in laboratoriumtesten gevormd in < 10% van de toegevoegde radioactiviteit. Deze metabolieten zijn wel relevant voor uitspoeling (ze worden aangetroffen in het percolaat van de lysimeters) maar niet majeur. Daarom worden ze niet beoordeeld voor het aspect persistentie.

 

Mancozeb bevat mangaan en zink. Omdat dit anorganische stoffen zijn, en hiermee per definitie persistent, voldoen mangaan en zink niet aan de norm voor persistentie zoals opgenomen in het Bmb. Derhalve dient voor de stoffen mangaan en zink aangetoond te worden:

i.   dat de toepassing van het bestrijdingsmiddel niet leidt tot een onaanvaardbare accumulatie van mangaan en zink, dan wel op de lange termijn geen gevolgen heeft voor de diversiteit en rijkdom van andere soorten dan de doelsoorten รฉn

ii.      dat de som van de concentratie van mangaan en zink, niet zodanig is dat 2 jaar na het tijdstip waarop het bestrijdingsmiddel voor het laatst is gebruikt in de bovenste
20 cm van de bodem op de plaats waar het bestrijdingsmiddel is gebruikt het MTR voor bodemorganismen en organismen die afhankelijk zijn van deze bodemorganismen wordt overschreden.

 

zink

Mancozeb bevat ca. 2,55% zink. De concentratie van zink in de bovenste 20 cm van de bodem na een jaarlijkse toepassing is berekend volgens Bijlage II van de Rumb 2000. Er wordt verondersteld dat er geen afbraak van zink optreedt, zodat de verwachte concentratie na
10 jaarlijkse toepassingen en twee jaar na de laatste toepassing het tienvoudige van deze concentratie is. In eerste instantie is geen rekening gehouden met interceptie door het gewas (worst case). De berekende Gp,10 is gebaseerd op R=100 % (geen afbraak) en getoetst aan de Maximum Permissible Addition (MPA=MTT) voor zink van 16 mg/kg bodem o.b.v. standaardbodem met een organisch stofgehalte van 10% (Crommentuijn et al., 19971). mangaan

Mancozeb bevat ca. 20% mangaan. De concentratie van mangaan in de bovenste 20 cm van de bodem na een jaarlijkse toepassing is berekend volgens Bijlage II van de Rumb 2000. Er wordt verondersteld dat er geen afbraak van mangaan optreedt, zodat de verwachte concentratie na 10 jaarlijkse toepassingen en twee jaar na de laatste toepassing het tienvoudige van deze concentratie is. In eerste instantie is geen rekening gehouden met interceptie door het gewas (worst case). De berekende Gp,10 is analoog aan Zn gebaseerd op R=100 % (geen afbraak) en dient evenals voor zink getoetst te worden aan de Maximum Permissible Addition (MPA=MTT). De bepaling van deze Maximaal Toelaatbare Toevoeging van mangaan wordt hieronder uitgewerkt.

In de studie โDetermination of the MPA (Maximum Permissible Addition) for manganese in soil according to the methods of the Netherlands, 2002โ zijn op basis van een literatuurrecherche 22 studies geselecteerd en geรซvalueerd volgens de criteria in Crommentuijn et al. (1997). De gegevens zijn samengevat voor ieder rapport teneinde een NOEC van mangaan voor bodemorganismen te bepalen. Alleen studies waarbij de hoeveelheid toegevoegd mangaan is gerapporteerd zijn gebruikt. Voor meerdere studies met dezelfde soort is de geometrische gemiddelde NOEC berekend. Bij verschillende eindpunten voor dezelfde soort is de laagste NOEC gebruikt. Statistische extrapolatie is gebruikt om de MTT te berekenen volgens de methode van Aldenberg en Slob. Er wordt een MTT van 39 mg Mn/kg soil dw voorgesteld op basis van het geharmoniseerde protocol volgens Kalf et al., 1999. Onderliggende gegevens betreffen 5 soorten planten, 4 soorten macro-invertebraten (waaronder de regenworm Eisenia fetida en de springstaart Orchesella cincta) en 9 soorten schimmels. Het merendeel van de referenties die door de aanvrager zijn geleverd ter onderbouwing van dit MTT voor mangaan is bij nadere evaluatie als niet betrouwbaar of niet bruikbaar beoordeeld. Veel studies zijn niet uitgevoerd met het juiste medium volgens geldende richtlijnen. Afgezien daarvan heeft de aanvrager bij het afleiden van het MTT geen onderscheid gemaakt tussen processen en soorten, welk onderscheid volgens het protocol van Traas (2001) wel zou moeten zijn gemaakt.

Door het RIVM is een aanvullende literatuurrecherche uitgevoerd zoals beschreven in Traas (2001). De uit deze literatuurrecherche geselecteerde gegevens voor processen zijn in tabel M.3 samengevat. Voor microbiรซle processen en enzymactiviteit zijn een EC10 en een NOEC beschikbaar. Een EC10 mag worden gebruikt als NOEC wanneer voor de desbetreffende soort geen NOEC beschikbaar is. De EC10 voor respiratie wordt daarom beschouwd als NOEC, waarmee er twee NOEC's beschikbaar zijn. Volgens het MTR-protocol moet een factor 100 worden toegepast op de laagste NOEC, hetgeen leidt tot een waarde van 0,66 mg/kg.

6.1.2 Leaching to shallow groundwater

The leaching potential of the a.i.โs metalaxyl-M, mancozeb and its metabolites ETU, EU, and EBIS is calculated in the first tier using Pearl 2.2.2. and the FOCUS Kremsmรผnster scenario. The new decision tree for leaching including the new model GeoPEARL has been released for use in risk assessment at the end of 2004. In a letter of minister Veerman of the department of Agriculture, Nature and Food quality he asked the CTB to anticipate on the revision of the Rumb (2000) concerning the assessment of leaching to groundwater. This request is based on article 3 of the Pesticide act (state of science) in combination with article 6 of the Regulation (new models). The methodology as described in the report "The new decision tree for the evaluation of pesticide leaching from soils", A.M.A van der Linden, J.J.T.I. Boesten, A.A. Cornelese, R. Kruijne, M. Leistra, J.B.H.J Linders, J.W. Pol, A. Tiktak and A.J Verschoor, RIVM report 601450019/2004, RIVM, Bilthoven (2004) has to be used.

Input variables are the actual application rate (1.6 versus 0.975 kg/ha for mancozeb and metalaxyl-M respectively), the crop (cabbage is taken as representative crop, because lettuce is not included in Pearl 2.2.2) and an interception value appropriate to the crop of 0.2 (early stage of leaf development) 2. For metabolites all available data concerning substance properties are regarded. Metabolites are modelled as parent. The application rate is corrected for formation rate and molecular weight relative to the parent substance when available. For CGA 108906, a metabolite of metalaxyl-M that only was found in the leachate of the lysimeter (max. 1.11 ยตg/L), no data are available on either adsorption or half-life. As this metabolite has already been declared non-relevant (see previous section), this is acceptable. No modelling of leaching is performed for this metabolite. For the other non-relevant and major soil metabolite of metalaxyl-M, CGA 62826, which is also found in the leachate of the lysimeter, there are data on adsorption and half-life. Therefore this metabolite is included in the modelling of leaching with PEARL 2.2.2.

Lysimeter/field leaching studies (in Dutch, taken from assessment Fubol Gold WG, decision of 01-04-2005, resulting from C-155.3.19, 28 February 2005)

Metalaxyl-M

Na doseringen van 360 g w.s./ha op aardappelen (twee lysimeters) werd metalaxyl-M in het percolaat van รฉรฉn lysimeter aangetroffen in een gemiddelde jaarconcentratie van 0,05 ยตg/L in het eerste en tweede jaar. Na dosering van 400 g w.s./ha op druiven (twee lysimeters) gevolgd door een toepassing van 400 g w.s./ha in het tweede jaar op รฉรฉn van beide lysimeters, varieerde de gemiddelde jaarconcentratie tussen <0,01 en 0,01 ยตg/L.


Voor de majeure metaboliet CGA 62826 werden concentraties van 0.25-4.12 ยตg/l gevonden. Voor CGA108906 (alleen gemeten in de lysimeters) zijn concentraties van 0.48-1.11 ยตg/l gevonden (zie eindpuntenlijst).

 

De lysimeterexperimenten zijn gesimuleerd met behulp van PESTLA 3.3. De verhouding tussen de gemeten en de gesimuleerde uitspoeling is een indicator voor de mate waarin het model de gemeten uitspoeling kan voorspellen. Het kan dienen als een factor waarmee voorspellingen voor andere scenario's, bijv. het Nederlands standaardscenario, gecorrigeerd worden. De volgende formule kan hiervoor worden gebruikt:

()


Voor het toepassingsschema van de lysimeter blijkt dat de gecorrigeerde concentratie voor metalaxyl kleiner is dan 0,1 ยตg/L.

Uit de twee lysimeterstudies komen de volgende correctiefactoren: 3,46 en 0,517 voor metalaxyl-M. Na middeling (gemiddelde correctiefactor = 2) worden deze factoren gebruikt om de concentraties in het bovenste grondwater te schatten. Omdat met deze methode is gecorrigeerd voor de onzekerheid in de modellering, wordt de uitkomst getoetst aan de norm van 0,1 ยตg/L. Gezien de lage concentraties voor de onderhavige toepassingen (< 0,001 ยตg/L in het standaardscenario uit de PEARL modellering) en de hoogte van de correctiefactor blijft de reeds getrokken conclusie van kracht en voldoen de onderhavige toepassingen aan de norm voor uitspoeling zoals opgenomen in de UB.

6.2 Fate and behaviour in water


6.2.1 Rate and route of degradation in surface water


The exposure concentrations of the active substances metalaxyl-M and mancozeb in the surface water are estimated for the various proposed uses using calculations of surface water concentrations (in a ditch of 30 cm depth), which originate from spray drift during application of the active substance. The spray drift percen­tage depends on the use. Concentrations in surface water are calculated using the model TOXSWA.

The metabolites of mancozeb, ETU, EU en EBIS, are major metabolites in the water phase of the tested water/sediment systems. Based on the available toxicity data, it can be concluded that they are much less toxic than the parent substance. Therefore it is assumed that the risk assessment for aquatic organisms can be made on the basis of the parent substance only. In view of this conclusion, there is no need to calculate exposure concentrations of ETU, EU and EBIS. For the active substances the following input is required (all on the basis of mean values):

Drinking water criterion

It follows from the decision of the Court of Appeal on Trade and Industry of 19 August 2005 (Awb 04/37 (General Act Administrative Law)) that the Ctb should for an authorisation, on the basis of the scientific and technical knowledge, considering the data submitted with the application, also test against the drinking water criterion as regards surface water intended for drinking water production to establish whether the product has no effect that is unacceptable for the environment. A mathematical model for this aspect is not available. This means that possibly available data cannot be taken into account adequately. It is therefore not possible to arrive at a scientifically well-based assessment of an expectation for this criterion. The Ctb has not been given the instruments for testing surface water from which drinking water is produced against the drinking water criterion. In order to meet the Court decision, however - from which it can be concluded that the Ctb should make an effort to arrive at a judgement on this point โ and as transitional period, to prevent that not a single authorisation can be granted in the period during which a model is being developed and data need to be generated for the application for authorisation, the Ctb has investigated whether the product under consideration and the active substances could give cause for concern about the drinking water criterion.


Mancozeb

Mancozeb is an existing active substance. From the general scientific knowledge collected by the Ctb about the product and its active substance, the Ctb concludes that there are in this case no concrete indications for concern about the consequences of this product for surface water from which drinking water is produced, when used in compliance with the directions for use. The Ctb does under this approach expect no exceeding of the drinking water criterion. At this point the product does not seem to have effects that are unacceptable for the environment.


Metalaxyl-M

As metalaxyl-M is a new active substance, there are no data available regarding its presence in surface water at drinking water abstraction points. At the moment, a preliminary decision tree is used to address this matter, while waiting for the final decision tree that is currently under construction by the Drinking Water Criterion Project Team (expected in 2006). The following procedure is derived from this preliminary decision tree: Because exceeding of the threshold value of 0.1 ยตg/L at drinking water abstraction points in surface water cannot be entirely ruled out for metalaxyl-M based on the predicted exposure concentrations in the ditch next to the arable land (as calculated with TOXSWA), an adequate risk assessment is required to ensure that the risk of exceeding the drinking water criterion at drinking water abstraction points in surface water is negligible. The Ctb has established a provisional and conservative procedure to enable expert judgement on this matter in anticipation of the final decision tree. In this procedure, a dilution factor of 10 and a residence time of 14 days are used to estimate surface water concentrations at the drinking water abstraction points. When expected concentrations are between 0.1 and 0.5 ยตg/L, post registration monitoring is required at the so-called blue junctions (as established in the Water Framework Directive). These are situated upstream from drinking water abstraction points. Thus, when the surface water concentrations at these locations are below 0.1 ยตg/L, it can be considered sufficiently certain that there will be no exceeding of the drinking water threshold at the drinking water abstraction points.

For metalaxyl-M, this procedure results in an estimated concentration of 1.22 ยตg/l divided by the dilution factor of 10= 0.12 ยตg/L. Taking into account the residence period of 14 days and the mean degradation half-life of metalaxyl-M in water/sediment systems of 47.5 days will result in a further decrease of this concentration with 15 %, yielding a final estimated concentration of 0.1 ยตg/L. Therefore, the application of Fubol Gold can only be allowed when an adequate risk assessment of the available monitoring data and/or post-registration monitoring, preferably at the blue junctions, is performed for metalaxyl-M.


An adequate risk assessment was provided by the applicant on April 24 2006 (Calculation of metalaxyl-M concentration in surface water at drinking water abstraction point).

In a meeting of the drinking water criterion working group installed by the ministries of agricultural and environment to draft a decision tree, a dilution factor of 10 and a travelling time of 6 days was proposed. Newer discussions in this working group brought in the Relative Area Treated (RAT) or a RAT factor as an alternative for the dilution factor of 10. Both approaches were argued for with the fact that the plant protection product will be applied only to a fraction of the area close to the ditch because only a share of the area will be of agricultural land use, regarding the agricultural area close to a ditch, the crop protection product is or will not be registered on all crops, in the crops with registered use the product is under competition with other products and the field will only be partly sprayed with the product under review.

Following the latest discussion, the present assessment takes into account the estimated relative treated area with metalaxyl-M as a result of the use of Fubol Gold, rather than an over-all dilution factor.

3. Calculation


CTB Toxswa PIEC calculation for metalaxyl-M applied in lettuce using the DT50 value of 47.5 days was calculated to be 1.22 ยตg/L.


First, the concentration due to the use in lettuce only is calculated:


PECsw2drw = 1.22 * [(1373/4152803) * 0.4 * 0.5] * [e โ[(ln2)/47.5] * 6] =


PECsw2drw = 1.22 * 6.61 x 10-5 *0.916 = 0.74 x10-4 ยตg/L.


Secondly, the calculation is presented for the total NL agricultural area relevant for metalaxyl-M use. Here, the worst-case PIEC from all uses indicated above has been used:


PECsw2drw = 2.86 * [(196630/4152803) * 0.4 * 0.5] * [e โ[(ln2)/47.5] * 6] =


PECsw2drw = 2.86 *0.00947 *0.916 = 0.025 ยตg/L.


These PECsw2drw values are below the 0.1 ยตg/L threshold value and therefore meet the criterion for surface water meant for drinking water production.


All worst case assumptions have been used for the calculation. The calculation will therefore be an overestimate of the concentration.


4. Monitoring data

In addition, RIWA Meuse has reported metalaxyl data for 2004 at location Keizersveer (see their annual report on http://www.riwa-maas.org/jaarverslag/index_nl.htm, Quality report 2004).

All 10 data points were below 0.05 ยตg/L, therefore the mean and 90 percentile value are also < 0.05.


From both the calculation and the available recent monitoring data at a relevant monitoring point, it is clear that the use of metalaxyl-M in the registered crops meets the criterion for surface waters meant for drinking water production.


Conclusion


The assumptions in the adequate risk assessment are reasonable and therefore agreed. If the calculation is carried out for each of the individual crops the total conecentration is 0.012 ยตg/L.


The expected concentration intended for drinking water production based on the calculations for metalaxyl-M is smaller than 0.1 ยตg/L for the proposed applications. Hence, the product under consideration could give no cause for concern about the drinking water criterion.


Furthermore the applicant has provided similar calculations for the other formulations based on metalaxyl-M authorized or under application in The Netherlands in order to show that the total use of metalaxyl-M will not lead to a concentration higher than 0.1 at the abstraction points of surface water intended for drinking water production.

It should also be noted that the above calculation is a worst case calculation since a market share of 100% is assumed. A market share of 100% is highly unlikely since the current Dutch market already consists of other products.

Therefore the use of the active substance metalaxyl-M will give no cause for concern about the drinking water criterion and all proposed applications of the active substance thiacloprid meet the standards for the drinking water criterion as laid down in the BUBG.

6.5 Conclusions regarding the environmental fate and behaviour

It can be concluded that:

  1. the active substances metalaxyl-M and mancozeb meet the standards for per­sis­tence in soil as laid down in the Regulation of Uniform Principles for Plant protection products (BUBG).

  2. the active substances metalaxyl-M and mancozeb and its metabolites meet the standards for leaching to the shallow groundwater as laid down in the BUBG.

  3. the active substance mancozeb meets the standards for the drinking water criterion as laid down in the BUBG.

  4. the active substance metalaxyl-M does meet the standards for the drinking water criterion as laid down in the BUBG.

Fish Species Sensitivity Distribution Study

10 species of freshwater fish were tested for 96 hours acute toxicity in shallow (30 cm), static sediment/water microcosms. Test material (Dithane M-45) was applied once in 5 test concentrations under the water surface. Analytical confirmation indicated that all initial concentrations were >80% of nominal, therefore, results were expressed as nominal initial concentrations.

The most sensitive fish species was rainbow trout 96 hours LC50 = 0.073 mg as/L (NOEC=0.050 mg as/L). Results in the other species of fish were (96 hr LC50โs mg as/L): fathead minnow 0.57; channel catfish 0.68; bluegill sunfish 0.84; three-spined stickleback 0.93; zebra fish 0.95; largemouth bass 1.0; guppy 1.3; golden medaka 1.4; common carp 1.7.


Invertebrate/Phytoplankton Microcosm study

No NOECcommunity could be derived because there were still long term effects at the lowest tested concentration (reduction of the abundance of clams). The study was conducted at pH 5.5-7: mancozeb hydrolysed very fast in acid environment and much slower under alkaline conditions. For this reason the study can be use in a risk evaluation of mancozeb in more or less acid surface waters.

Invertebrate/Phytoplankton Mesocosm study

The study is adequate for risk evaluation for phyto- and zoo-planckon communities and aquatic diptera. The Ecological Acceptable Concentration is 32 ยตg as/l applicable to aquatic risk assessment scenarios involving 8 or fewer applications.

Veldstudies

Bij een veldstudie in een wijngaard in Zwitserland is het middel vier maal toegepast in twee doseringen van respectievelijk 0,1875 en 2,5 kg/ha. Er was bij beide doseringen sprake van een significante reductie van het aantal mijten (bijna uitsluitend T. pyri) van 9 dagen na de

1e toepassing tot en met 27 dagen na de 4e toepassing. Bij een tweede veldstudie in een wijngaard in Frankrijk is het middel vier maal toegepast in twee doseringen van respectievelijk 0,19 en 2,5 kg/ha. Er was bij beide doseringen sprake van een significante reductie van het aantal mijten (bijna uitsluitend T. pyri) van 13 dagen na de 4e toepassing tot en met 49 dagen na de 4e toepassing.

In the Dutch Pesticide Law the Uniform Principles are implemented in the Regulation of Uniform Principles for Plant protection products (BUBG). This Regulation is also the legal basis for the Dutch specific criteria.


7.1 Effects on birds

Birds can be exposed to the active substances mancozeb and metalaxyl-M by natural food (sprayed insects, seeds, leafs), drinking water and as a result of secondary poisoning.


7.1.1 Natural food and drinking water

The threshold value for birds is based on the trigger from the BUBG. The threshold value for acute and short term exposure is set to 0.1 times the LD50 and LC50 value, and the threshold value for chronic exposure is set to 0.2 times the NOEC. In table M.11 an overview of toxicity data and resulting threshold values are presented. In the risk assessment a small bird with a body weight (BW) of 10 gram, a daily food intake (DFI) of 2.9 g/day and a daily water intake (DWI) van 3 g is chosen as representative target species.

Taking the results in table M.13into account, a high chronic risk for birds can be expected due to foraging at the proposed use. This risk is predominantly posed by mancozeb. Since the long term exposure is larger than the threshold value, a refinement of the risk assessment is carried out for mancozeb. The refinement is carried out for herbivorous and insectivorous birds separately.


Herbivorous birds

For herbivorous birds the risk assessment is carried out taking residue decline on the crop in between applications into account. For mancozeb a half-life on lettuce has been established at 5.9 days. This degradation rate on the crop is also representative for the decline in weeds between the crop (see earlier assessments for mancozeb). In determining the PIECfood a MAF (Multiple Application Factor) is applied. The PECfood, long is calculated as time-weighted average over a period of 28 days. See Table M.14 for results.

Insectivorous birds

For insectivorous birds the risk assessment is carried out under the assumption that there will be no accumulation due to repeated applications (i.e., n=1). Degradation of the active substance on insects is not taken into account in first instance. This results in a PIECfood of
1.6 kg/ha * 25 = 40 mg/kg feed. The threshold exceeding factor is 40/25 = 1.6. A risk still cannot be excluded.

In the further refinement, degradation of mancozeb on insects is considered conform earlier assessments (in Dutch, taken from assessment Fubol Gold WG, decision of 01-04-2005, resulting from C-155.3.19, 28 February 2005).


De toepassingen blijken niet te voldoen aan de chronische norm op basis van mancozeb voor insectivore vogels. Als verfijning wordt rekening gehouden met afname van residu in de tijd. In onderzoek naar residuen op kevers is een zeer snelle afname gemeten met een halfwaardetijd van 2 uur. Ook uit onderzoek naar residuen op gewassen, in water en in de bodem blijkt dat dithiocarbamaten weinig persistent zijn. De RMS neemt aan dat de afname van residuen van mancozeb op kleine insecten gelijk is aan die op grote insecten (beargumenteerd in addendum 3). Aangezien er maar รฉรฉn studie beschikbaar is, wordt het 95% betrouwbaarheidsinterval aangehouden leidend tot een DT50 van 13 uur (in Addendum 2 was sprake van 2 uur). Nederland kan instemmen met de mogelijkheid van extrapolatie van gegevens betreffende kleine insecten naar grote insecten. Echter, er zijn twijfels of รฉรฉn studie voldoende is om de onzekerheid te adresseren (zelfs met medeneming van het betrouwbaarheidsinterval), vooral omdat er weinig vergelijkbare studies zijn en SANCO/4145/2000 geen duidelijk richtsnoer (guidance) geeft. Als โrealistic worst caseโ wordt daarom in deze beoordeling uitgegaan van een DT50 voor residuen op kleine insecten van maximaal 1 dag.

7.1.2 Secondary poisoning

The risk as a result of secondary poisoning is assessed based on bioconcentration in fish and worms. Examination takes place against the chronic threshold value for birds of 0.2 * NOEC which leads to a threshold value of 25 mg/kg food for mancozeb and 180 mg/kg food for metalaxyl-M.


Fish

Assessment metalaxyl-M

For metalaxyl-M a BCF of 15 L/kg is available. The highest PECwater(28) (taken from paragraph 6.2.1.) amounts 0.94 ๏ญg/L = 0.00094 mg/L. The risk is then calculated as PECwater(28) * BCFfish / trigger value = 0.00094 * 15/180 = < 0.001. Since this is below 1, the risk for birds as a result of consumption of contaminated/exposed fish is considered to be small.


Assessment mancozeb

Since there are no experimental data the bioconcentration factor for fish (BCFfish) is calculated according to the HTB (v0.2). The logKow of mancozeb is 1.38, which leads to a BCFfish of
0.473 L water/kg fish. The highest PECwater(28) (taken from paragraph 6.2.1.) amounts 0.52 ๏ญg/L = 0.00052 mg/L. The risk is then calculated as PECwater(28) * BCFfish / trigger value = 0.00052 * 0.473/25 = < 0.001. Since this is below 1, the risk for birds as a result of consumption of contaminated/exposed fish is considered to be small.


Combination

The combined risk for Fubol Gold amounts < 0.001+ < 0.001 = < 0.002. Since this is below 1, the risk for birds as a result of consumption of contaminated/exposed fish is considered to be small.


Earthworms

Assessment metalaxyl-M

Since there are no experimental data the bioconcentration factor for earthworms (BCFworm) is calculated according to the HTB (v0.2).

The logKow of metalaxyl-M is 1.71, which leads to a BCFworm = 0.084 kg soil/kg worm.

The highest PECsoil(28) amounts, corrected to the soil wet weight, 0.132 mg/kg soil.

The risk is then calculated as PECsoil(28) * BCFworm / trigger value = 0.132* 0.084/180 = < 0.001. Since this is below 1, the risk for birds as a result of consumption of contaminated/exposed worms is considered to be small.


Assessment mancozeb

Since there are no experimental data the bioconcentration factor for earthworms (BCFworm) is calculated according to the HTB (v0.2).

The logKow of mancozeb is 1.38, which leads to a BCFworm = 0.039 kg soil/kg worm.

The highest PECsoil(28) amounts, corrected to the soil wet weight, 0.006 mg/kg soil.

The risk is then calculated as PECsoil(28) * BCFworm / trigger value = 0.006* 0.039/25 = < 0.001. Since this is below 1, the risk for birds as a result of consumption of contaminated/exposed worms is considered to be small.


Combination

The combined risk for Fubol Gold amounts < 0.001 + < 0.001 = < 0.002. Since this is below 1, the risk for birds as a result of consumption of contaminated/exposed worms is considered to be small. Hence, the proposed use meets the standards for secondary poisoning as laid down in the BUBG.


Conclusions birds


The proposed application of the product complies with the Regulation of Uniform Principles for Plant protection products (BUBG).

mancozeb

metalaxyl-M

7.3.2 Secondary poisoning

The risk as a result of secondary poisoning is assessed based on bioconcentration in fish and worms. Examination takes place against the chronic threshold value for mammals of 0.2*NOEC which leads to a threshold value of 55 mg/kg BW/d food for mancozeb and 250 mg/kg food for metalaxyl-M.


Fish

Assessment metalaxyl-M

For metalaxyl-M a BCF of 15 L/kg is available. The highest PECwater(28) (taken from paragraph 6.2.1.) amounts 0.94 ๏ญg/L = 0.00094 mg/L. The risk is then calculated as PECwater(28) * BCFfish / trigger value = 0.00094*15/250=<0.001. Since this is below 1, the risk for mammals as a result of consumption of contaminated/exposed fish is considered to be small.


Assessment mancozeb

Since there are no experimental data the bioconcentration factor for fish (BCFfish) is calculated according to the HTB (v0.2). The logKow of mancozeb is 1.38, which leads to a BCFfish of
0.473 L water/kg fish. The highest PECwater(28) (taken from paragraph 6.2.1.) amounts 0.52 ๏ญg/L = 0.00052 mg/L. Because the threshold value is expressed as mg/kg BW/d, PECfood has to be corrected with a factor of 0.13 for average daily fish intake according to the Guidance Document on Birds and Mammals, leading to a PEC of 0.00052*0.13= 0.000068 mg/kg BW/d.

The risk is then calculated as PECwater(28) * BCFfish / trigger value = 0.000068 * 0.473/55 = < 0.001. Since this is below 1, the risk for mammals as a result of consumption of contaminated/exposed fish is considered to be small.


Combination

The combined risk for Fubol Gold amounts < 0.001+ < 0.001 = < 0.002. Since this is below 1, the risk for mammals as a result of consumption of contaminated/exposed fish is considered to be small.


Earthworms

Assessment metalaxyl-M

Since there are no experimental data the bioconcentration factor for earthworms (BCFworm) is calculated according to the HTB (v0.2). The logKow of metalaxyl-M is 1.71, which leads to a BCFworm = 0.084 kg soil/kg worm. The highest PECsoil(28) amounts, corrected to the soil wet weight, 0.132 mg/kg soil. The risk is then calculated as PECsoil(28) * BCFworm / trigger value = 0.132* 0.084/180 = < 0.001. Since this is below 1, the risk for mammals as a result of consumption of contaminated/exposed worms is considered to be small.


Assessment mancozeb

Since there are no experimental data the bioconcentration factor for earthworms (BCFworm) is calculated according to the HTB (v0.2). The logKow of mancozeb is 1.38, which leads to a BCFworm = 0.039 kg soil/kg worm. The highest PECsoil(28) amounts, corrected to the soil wet weight, 0.006 mg/kg soil. Because the threshold value is expressed as mg/kg BW/d, PECfood has to be corrected with a factor of 0.13 for average daily worm intake according to the Guidance Document on Birds and Mammals, leading to a PEC of 0.006*1.4= 0.0084 mg/kg BW/d. The risk is then calculated as PECsoil(28) * BCFworm / trigger value = 0.0084* 0.039/55 = < 0.001. Since this is below 1, the risk for mammals as a result of consumption of contaminated/exposed worms is considered to be small.


Combination

The combined risk for Fubol Gold amounts < 0.001 + < 0.001 = < 0.002. Since this is below 1, the risk for mammals as a result of consumption of contaminated/exposed worms is considered to be small. Hence, the proposed use meets the standards for secondary poisoning as laid down in the BUBG.


Conclusions mammals


The proposed application of the product complies with the Regulation of Uniform Principles for Plant protection products (BUBG)

Op grond van deze gegevens zijn effecten bij de onderhavige toepassing echter niet uit te sluiten gezien de hogere dosering en frequentie (2,5 kg middel/ha, herhaalde bespuiting).

 

Hierdoor is een nadere risico-evaluatie noodzakelijk. De volgende veldstudiegegevens zijn beschikbaar.


Field studies (in Dutch, taken from assessment Fubol Gold WG, decision of 01-04-2005, resulting from C-155.3.19, 28 February 2005)

Deze gegevens zijn moeilijk te extrapoleren naar de onderhavige toepassing. Based on the data presented above the standards for non-target arthropods are not met. An adequate risk assessment of the in field effects for predatory mites and rove beetles according to the proposed instructions for use should be delivered. 7.5.2 Earthworms

The trigger value for acute toxicity to earthworms is based on the standards from the BUBG and amounts 0.1 * LC50. The initial PEC soil is examined against that value.

Since the logPow of both active substances is < 2, correction to the reference soil containing 4.7 % organic matter is not necessary. The trigger value for earthworms based on the 14-day LC50 (> 299.1 mg/kg) of the active substance mancozeb amounts > 29.9 mg/kg. The trigger value for earthworms based on the 14-day LC50 (830 mg/kg) of the active substance metalaxyl-M amounts 83.0 mg/kg.

7.5.3 Effects on soil micro-organisms

In the tested soils no long-term effects are observed on nitrogen and carbon metabolisation processes at application rates of 7.0 and 35.0 kg/ha with the formulation Fubol Gold. A significant reduction on respiration was observed within a few hours at the highest dose (which is much higher than the dose applied for). This effect was transient. Since the reduction percentage is below 25% after 28 days, the standards from the Regulation of Uniform Principles for Plant protection products (BUBG) regarding soil micro-organisms are met.


7.5.4 Effects on activated sludge

As the proposed application is for field only, the exposure to a sewage treatment plant (STP) and effects on activated sludge do not need to be examined. Therefore, the proposed application is excluded from examination against the standard for activated sludge as laid down in the Regulation of Uniform Principles for Plant protection products (BUBG).


7.5.5 Effects on non target-plants

Testing of the effect on non-target higher plants is not yet required. As there are data available, the risk assessment is performed according to the Guidance Document on Terrestrial Ecotoxicology. The risk assessment for non-target plants is based on an off-crop situation with a drift percentage of 10%. The exposure thus equals 0.1 * the application rate, which leads to a PEC of 250 g formulation/ha. Seedling emergence and vegetative vigour tests have been performed with Fubol Gold. The threshold value is 0.2 times the lowest EC50 value. This EC50 is > 4500 g formulation/ha for all tests, leading to a threshold value of > 900 g/ha. The ratio between EC50 and the exposure concentration is < 0.28. The risk for non-target plants is considered to be low.

Thus, the standards as described in the Guidance Document on Terrestrial Ecotoxicology for effects on non-target plants are met.

8. Efficacy


8.1 Efficacy evaluation

Dose justification

The dosage for use in lettuce is derived from the former authorisation of Ridomil Zeta 72 WP. This product was a combination of 640 grams of zineb and 80 grams of metalaxyl and had an authorised use in lettuce. The calculated amount of active substance metalaxyl (expressed as metalaxyl-m) used for Ridomil Zeta 72 WP is comparable with the amount used with Fubol Gold. Because zineb and mancozeb both belong to the group of dithiocarbamates, and based on multiple year-experience, it can be assumed that there will be no or hardly any difference in efficacy and phytotoxicity between both actives. In an earlier stage the use of Fubol Gold on lettuce has already been evaluated and assessed (C-142.3.4).

The applicant has submitted three new studies, comprising 11 trials. In these trials the WP- and WG-formulation are compared. Fubol Gold was tested in different dosages (3.0 and 2.5 kg/ha) and with single, two-times and three-times application. A single application did not provide enough control. The double and triple applications gave a good to very good level of control.


Conclusion


It was already concluded that the efficacy of Fubol Gold against Bremia in lettuce could be extrapolated from the other uses (i.e. potatoes, Helichrysum). Because the dosage is lowered and the formulation changed, the efficacy was tested in additional trials, and assessed. From these trials it can be concluded that Fubol Gold, when applied three times at a dose of 2,5 kg/ha and an interval of 7-1 days, gave a good control of powdery mildew. The product Fubol Gold complies with the Uniform Principles because it does, in accordance with article 2.1. give an adequate control of downy mildew in lettuce.



8.2 Harmful effects


8.2.1 Phytotoxicity

Fubol Gold has an authorisation for the use in potatoes, onions, tree nurseries and Helichrysum. In none of these crops it gives any unacceptable phytotoxicity or other harmful effects. In none of the 11 trials provided did any unacceptable phytotoxicity occur.


8.2.2 Yield

In none of the trials did any unacceptable effect on yield occur.


8.2.3 Effects on succeeding crops or substitution crops

As no effects on succeeding crops or substation crops have been found for products based on metalaxyl-m and mancozeb, it can be assumed that no effects will occur. For the growth of lettuce, substitution crops are not relevant.


8.2.4 Effects on plants or plant products to be used for propagation

As lettuce is grown for consumption, and not for propagation, this point is not relevant.


8.2.5 Effects on adjacent crops

As no unacceptable effects on adjacent crops have been found for products based on metalaxyl-m and mancozeb, it can be assumed that no effects will occur.


Conclusion


The product complies with the Uniform Principles because it does not, in accordance with article 2.2., induce any unacceptable side effects on plants or plant products, when used and applied in accordance with the proposed label.


8.3 Resistance

Metalaxyl-m belongs to the group of phenylamides and resistance and cross resistance is known for this active substance (e.g. against Pythium in bulbs and Phytophthora in potatoes.

The FRAC gives guidelines as to the use of this group of fungicides. They should be used preventively and the number of applications should be no more than 2-4 with a maximum interval of 14 days. The change for resistance against mancozeb is considered low, because of its multiple site of action. The active substance has been used for many years, without any problems with resistance. The combination of mancozeb and metalaxyl-m in Fubol Gold will reduce the risk of resistance development and this justifies the combination of the product.


Conclusion


The product complies with the Uniform Principles, article 2.1.3 as the level of control on the long term is not influenced by the use of this product because of the possible build up of resistance.


8.4 For vertebrate control agents: impact on target vertebrates

As no vertebrates are controlled, this point is not relevant.


8.5 Any other relevant data / information

No other data was provided, used or taken into account.
